name: Nishikawa v. Dulles
description: Nishikawa, a U.S. citizen, was forcibly conscripted into the Japanese Army. He was entitled to retain his American citizenship.

name: Brown v. United States
description: In a denaturalization complaint, a person cannot take the stand to testify in her own behalf and also claim the right to be free from cross-examination on matters raised by her own testimony on direct examination.

name: Perez v. Brownell
description: An American citizen moved to Mexico to avoid the draft and voted in local elections. Upon his return to the United States, he is not entitled to citizenship.

name: Rowoldt v. Perfetto
question: Was Rowoldt a member of the Communist Party within the definition of Internal Security Act of 1950?
description: The government failed to demonstrate Rowoldt's "meaningful relationship" with the Communist Party under the Internal Security Act and therefore his deportation was unwarranted.

name: United States v. Shotwell Manufacturing Company
question: Is it in the interest of justice to remand the case for findings on a pre-trial motion to suppress evidence in light of new evidence?

name: City of Chicago v. Atchison, Topeka & Santa Fe Railway Company
Denver Union Stock Yard Company v. Producers Livestock Marketing Association
Commissioner of Internal Revenue v. P. G. Lake, Inc.
Tank Truck Rentals, Inc. v. Commissioner of Internal Revenue
Commissioner of Internal Revenue v. Sullivan
Chicago, Milwaukee, St. Paul & Pacific Railroad Company v. Illinois
question: Did the district court correctly find that the ICC lacked the necessary evidence to support the imposition of the order raising intrastate commerce fares?

name: Local 1976, United Brotherhood of Carpenters and Joiners of America, A.F.L. v. National Labor Relations Board
Sinkler v. Missouri Pacific Railroad Company
Black v. Magnolia Liquor Company, Inc.
Public Service Commission of Utah v. United States
Andrew G. Nelson, Inc. v. United States
Cicenia v. Lagay
question: Did the state’s refusal to permit Cicenia to communicate with counsel during the policy interrogation deprive him of due process?
description: A case in which the Court held that a criminal defendant did not have a constitutional right to confer with counsel during police questioning.

name: Crooker v. California
question: Is a confession obtained during an interrogation in which the suspect asked for and was denied access to counsel obtained in violation of the suspect’s Fourteenth Amendment right to due process?
description: A case in which the Court held that a confession given after the defendant’s specific request for counsel was denied does not violate the Due Process Clause of the Fourteenth Amendment when there was evidence that the defendant was aware of his rights.

name: City of Detroit v. Murray Corporation of America
Cooper v. Aaron
question: Were Arkansas officials bound by federal court orders mandating desegregation?
description: A case in which the Court held that Arkansas officials were bound by federal court orders mandating desegregation.

name: Schaffer Transportation Company v. United States
International Union, United Automobile, Aircraft and Agricultural Implement Workers of America (UAW-CIO) v. Russell
question:
(1) Does a state court have jurisdiction over an action by a non-union employee against a union and its agent, for malicious interference with the employee’s lawful occupation during a strike?

(2) Was the jury’s $10,000.00 verdict excessive?

National Labor Relations Board v. Duval Jewelry Company of Miami, Inc.

First Unitarian Church for Los Angeles v. County of Los Angeles
question: Do the CRTC and California Constitution provisions requiring those applying for tax exemption to agree to an oath promising not to overthrow the government by violent means violate the First or Fourteenth Amendments?

Federal Trade Commission v. National Casualty Company
Stinson v. Atlantic Coast Line Railroad Company
United States v. New York, New Haven & Hartford Railroad Company
Grimes v. Raymond Concrete Pile Company
Staub v. City of Baxley
question: Does an ordinance requiring union organizers to obtain a permit before recruiting violate free speech?

name: Kent v. Dulles
question: Could the Executive's Passport Department defer or refuse the issuance of passports to individuals suspected of being Communists or of traveling abroad to further Communist causes?

McGee v. International Life Ins. Company
City of Tacoma v. Taxpayers of Tacoma
United States v. Procter & Gamble Company
Wiener v. United States
question: Did President Eisenhower have the authority to terminate Wiener's membership on the Commission?

name: National Labor Relations Board v. Wooster Division of Borg-Warner Corporation
Amerian Airlines, Inc. v. North American Airlines, Inc.
Byrd v. Blue Ridge Rural Electric Cooperative, Inc.
question: Did Byrd’s Seventh Amendment right to jury trial trump South Carolina’s law limiting recovery?
description: A case in which the Court held that a South Carolina law was essentially a procedural rule because it determined how immunity should be enforced, rather than affecting the substantive rights and obligations created by the state.

name: Northern Pacific Railway Company v. United States
American Trucking Associations, Inc. v. United States
question:
1. Did the Interstate Commerce Act preclude the Interstate Commerce Commission from issuing a certificate authorizing motor-carrier operations to a subsidiary of Rock Island and Pacific Railroad Company because the parent company was a railroad corporation?

2. Was the Interstate Commerce Commission’s conclusion that public interest required the continuation of service by Rock Island Motor Transit Company supported by substantial evidence?

name: Jung v. K. & D. Mining Company
Beilan v. Board of Education, School District of Philadelphia
question: Did the removal of a teacher for “incompetency” based on the teacher’s refusal to confirm or deny involvement in various subversive organizations violate the Due Process Clause of the Fourteenth Amendment?
description: A case in which the Court held that public officials such as teachers can be questioned about issues that are relevant to their fitness and suitability for public service.

National Association for the Advancement of Colored People v. Patterson
question: Did Alabama's requirement violate the Due Process Clause of the Fourteenth Amendment?
description: A case in which the Court ruled that Alabama's requirement for the NAACP to divulge the names and addresses of all of its members and agents in the state violated the Due Process Clause of the Fourteenth Amendment.
